{[show NS]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H6. From \HKQ764 there is no third honour to make a sequence, so lead fourth-best from your longest, strongest suit — the six.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3\N with 2 \S, 1 \H (the lone ace), 2 \D and 2 \C on top — seven sure tricks. West is marked with the long, strong \H behind your single stopper and looks to have no outside entry, so West is the danger hand. Hold up the \HA, then develop \C, where you can build four tricks and any loser goes to safe East. Leave the \S finesse alone — it loses straight to West.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H6, which looks like a fourth-best, suggesting five \H headed by honours. Hold up your \HA — duck once, and again if East follows — to leave East with none, so the suit can't be run if East gets in. Then go after \C for four tricks; lead toward dummy's honours and let any loser fall to East, the safe hand. Two \S, one \H, two \D and four \C make nine. The \S finesse is fatal here: it loses to West's \SQ and the long \H cash, so develop \C instead.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Nine tricks — two \S, one \H, two \D, four \C — with West's \H dead because the hold-up exhausted East. You spotted that the \C finesse loses safely while the \S finesse loses fatally, and chose accordingly. That's the avoidance theme exactly right.}
