Nine tricks, the \C doing the developing and the \HA hold-up keeping West off the lead. You found the safe line by losing only to East and refusing the fatal \S finesse. That's the avoidance idea handled just right.

[PLAY 6 S \DJ]
You have already knocked out clubs and cashed the \DK; now a low \D is led toward your hand, where you hold \DAJ4 with the \DQ still missing. The defender ahead of you plays low. Which \D do you play?
[WHY]
Play the \DJ - the finesse. The missing \DQ rates to sit over your \DAJ4 where the jack pins it, so the finesse brings in the extra trick; even on a loss it loses to East, the safe hand with no \H to lead. Rising with the \DA throws away the finesse and lets the \DQ score.}
