[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H3. Lead fourth-best from your long, strong \HKQ532 to build heart tricks while you still hold an entry to cash them.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3NT. Top tricks: the \HA, two top spades, two top diamonds and two top clubs — seven ready. West's hearts are the threat and the \HA is your only stopper, so you must keep West off lead. Build the ninth tricks in the SAFE suits: clubs (\CKJ82 opposite \CAT9) for a fourth trick by finessing into East, and a third diamond, also losing only to East. Take the top two spades only — do NOT finesse the \SJ, which would hand West the \SQ and the contract.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West led the \H3, a fourth-best look, so West likely has five hearts headed by the KQ — the danger hand you must shut out. HOLD UP the \HA: duck the first round and win the second, stripping East of hearts. Then develop clubs by leading toward dummy and finessing — if the finesse loses it loses to East's \CQ, who is now safe with no heart to play. Add a third diamond, again conceding only to East, and you reach nine. Resist the spade finesse: the \SJ finesse loses to West's \SQ, the one hand that can cash hearts against you. Spades give you their two top honours and nothing more.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Well played. By holding up and then taking only the finesses that lose to East, you kept West — the hand with the long hearts — forever off lead. The spade finesse was the bait; clubs and a long diamond were the safe nine.

