Nine tricks: two \S, one \H, three \D and three \C, with West's \H neutralised. The whole hand turned on which way to lose the lead — you kept the dangerous West off play and steered every losing finesse into the safe East. Nicely judged avoidance.

[PLAY 9 S \DJ]
You have cashed the \DK in dummy and now lead a low \D back toward your hand, where you hold \DAJ6 with the \DQ still out. East follows low. Which \D do you play?
[WHY]
Play the \DJ - the finesse. East followed low, so the \DQ rates to sit over your jack just where the finesse picks it up, and even if it loses it loses to East, the safe hand who can never reach West's hearts. Rising with the \DA instead would crash a winner and give the defence a diamond trick with the queen.}
